Imagine you are standing in a kitchen with an infinite supply of dirty plates. You have a very specific rule for cleaning up:

- Every time you start a new task (calling a method), you place one dirty plate on the kitchen table.
- When that task is completely finished (the method returns), you take that plate off the table and wash it.

Normally, this works perfectly. You put down a plate, do the work, and remove the plate. The pile never gets too high.
But what if a task requires you to start another identical task before you can finish the first one? You put down plate #1. 
To finish it, you must start task #2, so you put down plate #2. Task #2 requires task #3...

The Problem: You are continuously adding new plates to the pile, but because no task ever finishes, you never remove a single plate.
The Result: The pile of plates grows higher and higher until it violently crashes into the kitchen ceiling, shattering everywhere.

In the programming world, that moment the plates hit the ceiling is exactly what a StackOverflowException is.

## The Technical Reality

In C# and the .NET runtime, there is a special, fixed-size block of memory called the Call Stack. It is typically very small 
(usually around 1 Megabyte per thread). Every time a method is called, the runtime creates a "frame" (a plate) and places it 
on the Call Stack. This frame holds the method's local variables and instructions on where to return when it finishes. If a 
method calls itself endlessly (a concept known as Infinite Recursion), the runtime keeps stacking these frames in memory. 
Because the stack size is strictly limited, it quickly runs out of physical space. The runtime detects that the stack is 
overflowing its boundaries and immediately terminates the application to protect the rest of the system's memory.

## Let's Look at the Code

// We define a method whose only job is to call itself.
public void UpdateItself()
{
    // The program enters this method (Plate #1 on the stack)
    // Then it immediately calls itself again (Plate #2 on the stack)
    // Then it calls itself again (Plate #3 on the stack)...
    
    // There is no stopping condition!
    // BOOM! The stack hits the ceiling in a matter of milliseconds.
    UpdateItself(); 
}
